 for bestpractices and # Privacy Policy Page

## Overview
Create a standalone Privacy Policy page that clearly communicates data collection, usage, retention, processing, and user rights. The page must include opt-out instructions and data export/delete procedures, be accessible, and integrate with the project's existing design system. It should be suitable for both public viewing and for reference by admins drafting policy updates. Ensure all frontend code is robust against null/undefined values and follows the runtime safety rules described in the project context.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
- What this page is:
  - A legal/privacy policy page that documents how the ConverseForms platform collects, uses, stores, shares, and processes user data, including agent/form data, session logs, messages, and analytics.
  - It explicitly describes data retention timelines, purposes of processing, data transfers (if any), and the roles of data processors.
  - It provides clear user rights (access, export, deletion, withdrawal of consent where applicable) and the methods to exercise those rights.
  - It includes opt-out mechanisms for non-essential data processing (e.g., marketing communications) and opt-out paths for data collection in specific contexts (e.g., cookie consent, analytics).
  - It provides procedures for data export and data deletion requests for account owners, including required verification steps, expected timelines, and where to send requests (e.g., Data Protection Officer contact, support email).
- Goals:
  - Clearly present data collection categories (e.g., account data, form/agent data, usage analytics, messages/logs, cookies).
  - Communicate retention periods and deletion/erasure options.
  - Provide user-friendly export and deletion procedures with step-by-step guidance.
  - Align with global privacy standards (e.g., GDPR, CCPA) and the project’s legal posture; include a contact section for privacy inquiries.
- Connected features:
  - No direct feature integrations are required for this page, but it should be structured so future integrations (e.g., API-based data export, webhooks, account-level opt-outs) can be added easily.
- UI elements and visual guidance:
  - Policy Sections: Data Collected, How We Use Data, Data Sharing and Third-Party Processors, Data Retention, Data Security, User Rights (Access, Export, Deletion, Correction), Opt-Out Options, Data Export Procedure, Data Deletion Procedure, Cookies (if applicable), Changes to Policy, Contact Information.
  - Data Requests: Link or clear button to initiate data export or deletion requests (visible to account owners, with distinct callouts or a dedicated “Request Data Export” and “Request Data Deletion” inline action).
  - Contact Info: Privacy or Data Protection Officer contact email, support channel, and a visible “Submit a request” form section or link if applicable.
  - Visual guidance: clean typographic hierarchy, ample white space, accessible contrast, and structured sections with anchor links for quick navigation.
- API integrations:
  - No external API calls are required for this page. The page should be static/SEO-friendly content. It should be ready to pull in dynamic policy blocks if the project evolves, but no live API integration is mandated for this task.

## Components to Build
- PrivacyPolicyPage component
  - Props: none or optional data blocks for policy sections (to support future dynamic content).
  - State: none required beyond local UI states (e.g., expandable sections) with safe defaults.
  - Accessibility: landmark role="main", headings in logical order, skip navigation link, ARIA attributes for any collapsible sections.
- PolicySection component
  - Props: id, title, content, optional subpoints.
  - Behavior: render titled sections with optional subsections; support collapsible expand/collapse for long sections if desired.
- RequestSection component
  - Props: list of request types (Export Data, Delete Data), account owner visibility rules.
  - Behavior: present clearly labeled actions or links to initiate data export/deletion; require minimal interaction to comply with privacy standards.
- ContactSection component
  - Props: contactName, email, phone (optional), address (optional)—all optional values guarded.
  - Behavior: render contact details with proper semantics; ensure mailto: and tel: links are accessible.
- Toast/Modal component (optional)
  - For confirming policy updates or submitting a data export/deletion request (used if you implement inline submission workflow later).
- FooterSection (optional)
  - Consistent with site-wide footer; include a link to Privacy Policy for ease of access.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Page layout and structure
  - Create a centered container with a max width of 1100–1200 px and horizontal padding 24–36 px.
  - Use 12-column responsive grid semantics; policy content should be readable on all devices.
  - Each policy section should include a header (H2) and body text with optional subpoints; anchor links for internal navigation (e.g., #data-collection, #retention).
- UI components and interactions
  - Typography hierarchy follows the specified design system (see Visual Style section below).
  - Implement collapsible policy sections if content length warrants it or keep all sections expanded by default for readability.
  - Data Requests section should present two prominent actions: “Request Data Export” and “Request Data Deletion” as primary CTAs.
  - Ensure all inputs/interactive elements guard against null/undefined values before rendering.
- Accessibility
  - Semantic HTML (main, section, h1, h2, p, ul/li).
  - Keyboard navigable, with visible focus states matching design tokens.
  - Color contrast meeting WCAG 2.1 AA at minimum.
- Runtime safety
  - Guard all arrays and texts; use data ?? [] patterns when mapping content sections if content is fetched or dynamic.
  - Example: (sections ?? []).map(...) and Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - Initialize useState with appropriate defaults: useState<PolicySection[]>([]) for lists, useState<string>("") for strings where applicable.
  - Validate API-like shapes defensively (even if static): const sections = Array.isArray(policySections?.sections) ? policySections.sections : [].
  - Optional chaining for nested properties, with defaults.
- Styling and design system adherence
  - Colors, typography, spacing, borders, and shadows must align with the Visual Style section.
  - Use the defined gradient/overlay, card styling, and UI treatments for consistency.
- Data attributes and testing hooks
  - Add data-testid or aria-labels where appropriate to facilitate testing (e.g., data-testid="privacy-export-button").

### Backend
- Not required to implement real backend endpoints for this task since the Project Context specifies no APIs connected. However, you should prepare the frontend to accommodate future integration:
  - Define API contract placeholders (commented) for data export and deletion requests:
    - POST /privacy/export-request with payload { userId }
    - DELETE /privacy/data-deletion-request with payload { userId, reason }
  - Ensure the frontend only calls these when backend endpoints exist and that responses would be handled safely (guard against null responses).

### Integration
- Data flow
  - The page should render static policy content by default, with optional dynamic blocks if content is loaded from a CMS later.
  - If you introduce dynamic sections, implement a safe loader that uses data ?? [] and guards with Array.isArray checks.
- State synchronization
  - Use local UI state for collapsible sections; no global state dependencies are required for this page.

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on the Privacy Policy page from the site footer or navigation.
2. User reads clearly organized sections describing data collection, usage, retention, and processing.
3. User identifies opt-out options in the Opt-Out Options section and can access the data export or deletion procedures.
4. If the user is the account owner and wishes to export data or delete data, they click the prominent “Request Data Export” or “Request Data Deletion” actions.
5. If an inline modal/toast is used, user confirms submission; otherwise a guidance message appears explaining the next steps and expected timelines.
6. Users can locate contact information in the Contact Information section to reach the privacy team or Data Protection Officer for further questions.
7. Any policy updates or changes are listed in the Changes to Policy section with the effective date.

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models
  - PolicySection (for potential dynamic loading in the future)
    - id: string
    - title: string
    - body: string
    - subpoints?: string[]
  - ExportRequest (placeholder shape for future API)
    - userId: string
    - requestedAt: string (ISO)
    - status: 'pending' | 'completed' | 'rejected'
  - DeletionRequest (placeholder shape for future API)
    - userId: string
    - reason?: string
    - requestedAt: string (ISO)
    - status: 'pending' | 'completed' | 'rejected'

- API Endpoints (placeholders)
  - POST /privacy/export-request
    - Body: { userId: string }
    - Response: { success: boolean, message?: string, requestId?: string }
  - DELETE /privacy/data-deletion-request
    - Body: { userId: string, reason?: string }
    - Response: { success: boolean, message?: string, requestId?: string }

- Security
  - If implementing actual endpoints later, ensure authentication checks (e.g., user must be logged in to request data export/deletion).
  - Validate input payloads on the client before sending (e.g., non-empty userId, optional reason length limits).

- Validation
  - Ensure all content strings are non-null; fallback to empty strings where dynamic data could be missing.
  - All array mappings guarded using (sections ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(sections) ? sections.map(...) : [].

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Privacy Policy page renders with all required sections: Data Collected, How We Use Data, Data Sharing and Processors, Data Retention, Data Security, User Rights, Opt-Out Options, Data Export/Deletion Procedures, Cookies (if applicable), Changes to Policy, Contact Information.
- [ ] All interactive elements (export/delete actions) are accessible, clearly labeled, and styled per design guidelines.
- [ ] No runtime errors occur if policy content is empty or partially loaded; all array/map operations guard against null/undefined.
- [ ] Use useState with appropriate defaults for any local state; initial values are non-null and typed (e.g., useState<PolicySection[]>([]) ).
- [ ] All API placeholders are defined, with safe guards in code paths that would call them, ready for future integration.
- [ ] Visual style and typography strictly follow the provided Visual Style guidelines, including color palette, typography, spacing, and card patterns.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Use the specified color palette and contrast levels.
- Maintain typographic hierarchy (H1/H2/body/labels) with consistent spacing.
- Implement accessible, readable, and scannable content blocks.
- Keep interactions subtle, fast, and non-disruptive; avoid heavy animations.
- Ensure the page is responsive, with content readable on mobile and desktop.

